<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1930,2037]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,498]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="7" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1930,1956]" pageId="7" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Length of male 
<quantity box="[489,586,1931,1957]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
. Ground color stramineous, heavily mottled with brown; anteclypeus, mesonotal triangles, scutellum apex, mesosternum, and abdominal terga dark brown; pronotum with extensive symmetrical brown markings anteriorly; forewing without distinct markings. Male pygofer (fig. 3D) with dor- sal appendage arising near midlength, short, tapered, curved mesad; ventral appendage long, slender, extended dorsomesad and crossing midline; lobe between appendages broadly rounded, weakly sclerotized near margin. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[340,475,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,255,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[245,1323,197,1410]" captionTargetId="figure-184@11.[244,1342,194,1427]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. New North American spp. of Neozygina, male pygofer (A, D, G, J, M, O, R, U, X), aedeagus in lateral (B, E, H, K, N, P, S, V, Y, AA) and posterior (C, F, I, L, Q, T, W, Z) views. A–C, N. antlera; D–F, N. chiapensis; G–I, N. hondurensis; J–L, N. mandibulata; M–N, N. obsoleta; O–Q, N. potosiensis; R–T, N. sonorensis; U–W, N. veracruzensis; X–Z, N. zapatai; AA, N. sordida." pageId="8" pageNumber="35">Figs. 3E, F</figureCitation>
) with preatrium nearly as long as shaft; shaft broad basally, slender and curved dorsad distally, with pair of slender posterolaterally directed spines arising adjacent to dorsal apodeme, apex with pair of short laterally directed processes; gonopore apical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
